steps.content:
Rearrange to solve for $h$. Note that the exact value of $\tan(60^\circ)$ is $\sqrt{3}$.

$$
\begin{aligned}
h &= 60 \times \tan(60^\circ) \\
h &= 60\sqrt{3} \text{ m}
\end{aligned}
$$

parts.markscheme:
Length of AC is given as $\mathrm{AC}^{2}=13^{2}+12^{2} \quad[\mathrm{M} 1][\mathrm{A} 1]$

$$
\begin{array}{lrl}
\mathrm{AC} & =\sqrt{\left(13^{2}+12^{2}\right)} & {[\mathrm{M} 1]} \\
\mathrm{AC} & =\sqrt{313} & {[\mathrm{~A} 1]}
\end{array}
$$

Length of AD is given as $\mathrm{AD}^{2}=(\sqrt{313})^{2}+5^{2} \quad[\mathrm{M} 1][\mathrm{M} 1]$

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
\mathrm{AD}=\sqrt{(313+25)} & {[\mathrm{A} 1]} \\
\mathrm{AD}=\sqrt{338} & {[\mathrm{M} 1]}
\end{array}
$$

The angle of elevation from A to E is $\angle \mathrm{EAB}$
[M1]

$$
\begin{array}{lc}
\tan \angle \mathrm{EAB}=\frac{5}{13} & {[\mathrm{M} 1][\mathrm{A} 1]} \\
\angle \mathrm{EAB}=\tan ^{-1}\left(\frac{5}{13}\right) & {[\mathrm{M} 1]} \\
\angle \mathrm{EAB} \approx 21.1^{\circ} & {[\mathrm{A} 1]}
\end{array}
$$

The angle of elevation from A to D is $\angle \mathrm{DAC}$ [M1]

$$
\begin{array}{lrl}
\tan \angle \mathrm{DAC}=\frac{5}{\sqrt{313}} & {[\mathrm{M} 1][\mathrm{A} 1]} \\
\angle \mathrm{DAC}=\tan ^{-1}\left(\frac{5}{\sqrt{313}}\right) & & {[\mathrm{M} 1]} \\
\angle \mathrm{DAC} \approx 15.8^{\circ} & & {[\mathrm{A} 1]}
\end{array}
$$

steps.content:
Isolate $h$ by multiplying both sides by $\sin 65^{\circ}$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
h &= \frac{100 \times \sin 65^{\circ}}{\sin 90^{\circ}} \\
h &= \frac{100 \times \sin 65^{\circ}}{1} \\
h &= 100 \times \sin 65^{\circ}
\end{aligned}
$$

(Note: $\sin 90^{\circ} = 1$)

